xcuse</h2>\n\n<p>The following aren’t usually accepted as a reasonable excuse:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you relied on someone else to send your return and they didn&rsquo;t</li>\n  <li>your cheque bounced or payment failed because you didn’t have enough money</li>\n  <li>you didn’t get a reminder from <abbr title=\"Her Majesty's Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr></li>\n  <li>you registered for the <abbr title=\"Her Majesty's Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> online service after the tax return deadline</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>How to appeal</h2>\n\n<p>You can <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://search2.hmrc.gov.uk/kb5/hmrc/forms/view.page?record=3ScvEs7_4vk&amp;formId=6706\" title=\"Self Assessment appeal form\">fill in an appeal form</a> explaining the problem as soon as you know your return or payment are late.</p>\n\n<p>If <abbr title=\"Her Majesty's Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> sends you a penalty letter, you can use the appeal form that comes with it.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Only the nominated partner can appeal against penalties for sending partnership tax returns late.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Deadlines</h2>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You must appeal within 30 days of the date on a penalty letter from <abbr title=\"Her Majesty's Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If you appeal later, <abbr title=\"Her Majesty's Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> will look at the information you give them and decide if they will consider your appeal.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/self-assessment-appeals/appeal-against-a-tax-bill","slug":"appeal-against-a-tax-bill","order":2,"title":"Appeal against a tax bill","body":"<h2>If your tax bill is wrong</h2>\n\n<p>If you think your tax bill is wrong because you made a mistake on your tax return you don&rsquo;t need to appeal - you may be able to <a href=\"/self-assessment-tax-returns/corrections\" title=\"Correcting Self Assessment tax returns\">correc