yer Reference number\">UTR</abbr>) number and you can then send your tax return to <abbr title=\"Her Majesty's Revenue and Customs\">HMRC</abbr>.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Before you register</h2>\n\n<p>You’ll need your: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a href=\"/national-insurance-number\" title=\"Get a National Insurance number\">National Insurance number</a> </li>\n  <li>personal contact details - eg address</li>\n  <li>business details - eg business address, date you started self-employment or joined a partnership</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re registering a new business partnership, you must be the &lsquo;nominated partner&rsquo; (the partner responsible for sending in the partnership tax return).</p>\n\n<h2>Deadline</h2>\n\n<p>You should register by 5 October following the end of the tax year you need to send a tax return for. This way, you&rsquo;ll have enough time to complete registration before the tax return and any tax is due. You may have to pay a penalty if you register late.</p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example</strong>  </p>\n\n<p>Register by 5 October 2012 to send a 2011 to 2012 tax return.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>How to register</h2>\n\n<p>How you register depends on your circumstances. </p>\n\n<p>New sole traders and business partnerships can register for Self Assessment and get an online account (known as a &lsquo;Government Gateway&rsquo; account) at the same time. This lets you send your tax return online. </p>\n\n<table>\n  <thead>\n    <tr>\n      <th>Your circumstance</th>\n      <th>Your reason for registering</th>\n      <th>How to register</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td>New sole trader</td>\n      <td>You&rsquo;ve not been registered before</td>\n      <td><a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://online.hmrc.gov.uk/registration/newbusiness\" title=\"Register for Self Assessment - new sole trader\">Sole trader - register for Self Assessment</a></td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Existing sole trader</td>\n      <td>You&rsq